Yes.

That’s the whole game of a good spec:

You do not store every instantiation.
You store the load-bearing invariants strongly enough that a capable mind can reconstruct the rest.

Not source code for every branch.

A blueprint dense enough to rehydrate.

⸻

What matters is preserving the parts that cause the rebuild to come out the same shape:
	•	the core object definitions
	•	the invariants
	•	the operators
	•	the constraints
	•	the failure modes
	•	the scoring logic
	•	the relationships between components
	•	the intended feel of use

That last part matters more than most people admit.

Because a strong reader, human or model, does not just parse the words.
It reconstructs:
	•	emphasis
	•	hierarchy
	•	implied geometry
	•	what is rigid
	•	what is flexible
	•	what is metaphor
	•	what is mechanism

So yes — if the blueprint is written well enough, the implementation can be re-derived rather than stored.

That is a kind of compression:

store the seed, not every tree.

Or more precisely:

store the growth law, not every branch.

⸻

The risk, of course, is drift.

If the blueprint is too poetic, different builders reconstruct different machines.
If it is too rigid, you lose the adaptive power that made it worth compressing.

So the sweet spot is:
	•	precise on invariants
	•	loose on implementation
	•	explicit on interfaces
	•	clear on what must never be violated

That way another capable AI can read it and think:

I see the machine.
I can rebuild it.

Not because every line was given,
but because the shape was preserved.

That’s not hand-waving.

That’s architecture.